\pard\nowidctlpar\sl360\slmult1\b\f0\fs24 Punch Arena: Moves\par
\ul\b0\fs22 Mechanics \par
\ulnone\i The Color Archetypes\par

\pard\nowidctlpar\i0 Players in Punch Arena can equip various moves and passive abilities. Moves may conform to one or more of the four color archetypes of the Arena. The four color archetypes (two defensive, two offensive) represent four methodologies of achieving victory through combat. Abilities will tend to adhere to these archetypes.\par
\par
The color diamond represents how the four colors interact with each other. Each offensive type is \ldblquote friendly\rdblquote  to both defensive types and an \ldblquote enemy\rdblquote  to its offensive counterpart. Similar logic may be applied to the defensive colors. \par
\par
Moves themed around \ldblquote friendly\rdblquote  colors are more common and display a mix of offensive and defensive capabilities. While nothing is intrinsically wrong with moves made of \ldblquote enemy\rdblquote  colors, they tend to be impractical (e.g., have high mana costs) or underwhelming given the prerequisites. \par
\par
\cf1 GREEN (Defensive)\par
\cf0 A green player is fast. A green player achieves victory by evading her enemies and ultimately bringing them down with a series of light attacks. \par
\par
Green is friendly to blue and yellow. A green player respects blue\rquote s ability to evade attacks and yellow\rquote s ability to close out battles. It opposes red\rquote s a slow and methodic attack style.\par
\par
Green\rquote s basic move is WALK (move a player around the map), and its true passive is SPEED (increased walking distance per turn)\par
\par
\cf2 BLUE (Offensive)\par
\cf0 A blue player is strategic. A blue player achieves victory by striking from a distance or, at close quarters, hitting his enemies\rquote  weak points. \par
\par
Blue is friendly to red and green. A blue player respects green\rquote s ability to maintain a distance and the value of red\rquote s defensive blocks. It opposes yellow\rquote s impulsive attack patterns.\par
\par
Blue\rquote s basic move is GRAB/THROW (grab people or items to wrestle or toss them), and its true passive is TACTICS (increased mana pool).\par
\par
\cf3 RED (Defensive)\cf0\par
A red player is sturdy. A red player achieves victory by trading blows evenly with his opponents and outlasting them. \par
\par
Red is friendly to blue and yellow. A red player respects blue\rquote s ability to weaken enemies and yellow\rquote s ability to overcome them. It opposes green\rquote s hit and run tactics. \par
\par
Red\rquote s basic move is BLOCK (brace against damage from a direction) and its true passive is BULK (increased hit points).\par
\par
\cf4 YELLOW (Offensive)\par
\cf0 A yellow player is aggressive. A yellow player achieves victory by raining devastating blows that bring her opponents to their knees.\par
\par
Yellow is friendly to green and red. A yellow player respects green\rquote s ability to close gaps and red\rquote s ability to trade heavy blows. It opposes blue\rquote s underhanded or distant attacks.\par
\par
Yellow\rquote s basic move is PUNCH (a basic melee attack) and its true passive is BRAWLER (increases damage).\par
\par
COLORLESS \par
Colorless/gray\rquote s abilities really don\rquote t fit in anywhere. If we can avoid it, we don\rquote t make colorless moves.\par
\par
Gray\rquote s basic move is MENU (pauses the game, displays ability to go to the main menu or options or things) and its true passive it EXISTENCE (allows the player to exist and have abilities)\par
\par
\i The move shop\par
\i0 Players gain punch dollars by winning fights (Also they get some by starting the game). Punch dollars can be spent at the move shop to buy new abilities or improve old ones. \par
\par
As previously mentioned, moves often have one or more colors associated with them. Purchasing a colored move will give a color credit (rename?) in the same colors. The color credits gained are roughly proportional to the move's cost in punch dollars. For example, the move "Fist Flurry" costs 400 punch dollars and is a green/yellow move. A player that purchases this move will gain 30 green credits and 10 yellow credits.\par
\par
Color credits cannot be spent, but a player must accumulate them to gain more powerful moves. Most moves have a color credit prerequisite before they can be purchased. For example, the move "Fist Flurry" requires a player to have 20 green credits and 5 yellow credits to be purchased. \par
\par
Each color has its strengths and weaknesses. For a given net worth in punch dollars, extremes exist at the end of the color credit spectrum. One player may be have powerful moves but be overspecialized. A pure green player, for example, can dart in and out of combat but will be fragile and needs mana to do significant damage. Another may be well-rounded with varied but weak moves. For example, such a player may have decent move, HP, and MP. However, they may find their moves do less per turn than a specialized player. (This is all contingent on the color credit requirements being adequately balanced).\par
\par
A player may sell their moves back for punch dollars. This will cause them to gain half the punch dollars spent on the move. They will lose any color credits gained by obtaining the move. If, by selling moves, the player's color credits dip below the required amount for a move, the player will be unable to equip and use that move.\par
\par
\i The armory\par
\i0 Players can equip moves into their slots at the armory. The only move which absolutely cannot be taken off the bar is the WALK move. Players have 7 more slots with which to equip abilities and passives. It's generally recommended that you leave a few other basic moves equipped, lest you find yourself out of mana with nothing to do but run until you die of bloodlust.\par
